ut":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778118670206,"responseId":"resp_0d371f2cfb221f1c0169fbf00e70f88191ae903e2e6f1e1817"}}
{"type":"message","id":"1093afca","parentId":"2e6d0a06","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:51:14.648Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_DGIZTMiO2qAdldpxNaHGpF5t|fc_0d371f2cfb221f1c0169fbf01241108191bdbf82a10dcf2e6b","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:65:- Session identifiers (`sessionKey`, session IDs, labels) are routing selectors, not authorization tokens.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:219:- **Network exposure** (Gateway bind/auth, Tailscale Serve/Funnel, weak/short auth tokens).\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:236:- **Slack tokens**: config/env (`channels.slack.*`)\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:608:OpenClaw strips common self-hosted LLM chat-template special-token literals from wrapped external content and metadata before they reach the model. Covered marker families include Qwen/ChatML, Llama, Gemma, Mistral, Phi, and GPT-OSS role/turn tokens.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:612:- OpenAI-compatible backends that front self-hosted models sometimes preserve special tokens that appear in user text, instead of masking them. An attacker who can write into inbound external content (a fetched page, an email body, a file contents tool output) could otherwise inject a synthetic `assistant` or `system` role boundary and escape the wrapped-content guardrails.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:616:This does not replace the other hardening on this page — `dmPolicy`, allowlists, exec approvals, sandboxing, and `contextVisibility` still do the primary work. It closes one specific tokenizer-layer bypass against self-hosted stacks that forward user text with special tokens intact.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:669:chat-template special tokens are handled. If a backend tokenizes literal strings\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:671:structural chat-template tokens inside user content, untrusted text can try to\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:677:tokens in user-provided content when available. Hosted providers such as OpenAI\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:970:- `openclaw.json`: config may include tokens (gateway, remote gateway), provider settings, and allowlists.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:972:- `agents/<agentId>/agent/auth-profiles.json`: API keys, token profiles, OAuth tokens, and optional `keyRef`/`tokenRef`.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:1007:- Add custom patterns for your environment via `logging.redactPatterns` (tokens, hostnames, internal URLs).\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:1284:3. Rotate provider/API credentials (WhatsApp creds, Slack/Discord tokens, model/API keys in `auth-profiles.json`, and encrypted secrets payload values when used).\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/audit-checks.md:25:| `fs.config.perms_group_readable`                              | warn          | Group users can read config tokens/settings                                          | filesystem perms on config file                                                                      | yes      |\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/audit-checks.md:26:| `fs.config.perms_world_readable`                              | critical      | Config can expose tokens/settings                                                    | filesystem perms on config file                                                                      | yes      |\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/audit-checks.md:31:| `fs.auth_profiles.perms_readable`                             | warn          | Others can read API keys and OAuth tokens                                            | `agents/<agentId>/agent/auth-profiles.json` perms                                                    | yes      |\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/prometheus.md:96:| `openclaw_model_tokens_total`                 | counter   | `agent`, `channel`, `model`, `provider`, `token_type`                                     |\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/prometheus.md:145:sum by (provider) (rate(openclaw_model_tokens_total[1m]))\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/operator-scopes.md:38:| `operator.pairing`      | Device and node pairing management, including listing, approving, rejecting, removing, rotating, and revoking pairing records or device tokens.                                       |\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/health.md:33:- Diagnostics are enabled by default. The gateway records operational facts unless `diagnostics.enabled: false` is set. Memory events record RSS/heap byte counts, threshold pressure, and growth pressure. Liveness warnings record event-loop delay, event-loop utilization, CPU-core ratio, and active/waiting/queued session counts when the process is running but saturated. Oversized-payload events record what was rejected, truncated, or chunked, plus sizes and limits when available. They do not record the message text, attachment contents, webhook body, raw request or response body, tokens, cookies, or secret values. The same heartbeat starts the bounded stability recorder, which is available through `openclaw gateway stability` or the `diagnostics.stability` Gateway RPC. Fatal Gateway exits, shutdown timeouts, and restart startup failures persist the latest recorder snapshot under `~/.openclaw/logs/stability/` when events exist; inspect the newest saved bundle with `openclaw gateway stability --bundle latest`.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-agents.md:561:- `isolatedSession`: when true, each heartbeat runs in a fresh session with no prior conversation history. Same isolation pattern as cron `sessionTarget: \"isolated\"`. Reduces per-heartbeat token cost from ~100K to ~2-5K tokens.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-agents.md:564:- Heartbeats run full agent turns — shorter intervals burn more tokens.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:539:- Native slash callbacks are authenticated with the per-command tokens returned\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-channels.md:762:- Env tokens only apply to the **default** account.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/heartbeat.md:445:Don't put secrets (API keys, phone numbers, private tokens) into `HEARTBEAT.md` — it becomes part of the prompt context.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/heartbeat.md:472:Heartbeats run full agent turns. Shorter intervals burn more tokens. To reduce cost:\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/heartbeat.md:474:- Use `isolatedSession: true` to avoid sending full conversation history (~100K tokens down to ~2-5K per run).\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-tools.md:452:    - `models.providers.*.maxTokens`: default output-token cap for models under this provider when the model entry does not set `maxTokens`.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-tools.md:486:    - `plugins.entries.amazon-bedrock.config.discovery.defaultMaxTokens`: fallback max output tokens for discovered models.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/protocol.md:25:  body, attachment contents, raw frame body, tokens, cookies, or secret values.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/protocol.md:324:    - `diagnostics.stability` returns the recent bounded diagnostic stability recorder. It keeps operational metadata such as event names, counts, byte sizes, memory readings, queue/session state, channel/plugin names, and session ids. It does not keep chat text, webhook bodies, tool outputs, raw request or response bodies, tokens, cookies, or secret values. Operator read scope is required.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/protocol.md:414:    - Chat execution still uses `chat.history`, `chat.send`, `chat.abort`, and `chat.inject`. `chat.history` is display-normalized for UI clients: inline directive tags are stripped from visible text, plain-text tool-call XML payloads (including `<tool_call>...</tool_call>`, `<function_call>...</function_call>`, `<tool_calls>...</tool_calls>`, `<function_calls>...</function_calls>`, and truncated tool-call blocks) and leaked ASCII/full-width model control tokens are stripped, pure silent-token assistant rows such as exact `NO_REPLY` / `no_reply` are omitted, and oversized rows can be replaced with placeholders.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/protocol.md:418:  <Accordion title=\"Device pairing and device tokens\">\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/protocol.md:433:    - `node.canvas.capability.refresh` refreshes scoped canvas-capability tokens.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/protocol.md:623:- Additional `hello-ok.auth.deviceTokens` entries are bootstrap handoff tokens.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/protocol.md:629:- Device tokens can be rotated/revoked via `device.token.rotate` and\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/protocol.md:655:- Gateways issue tokens per device + role.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/doctor.md:100:    - Model auth health: checks OAuth expiry, can refresh expiring tokens, and reports auth-profile cooldown/disabled states.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/doctor.md:340:    Doctor inspects OAuth profiles in the auth store, warns when tokens are expiring/expired, and can refresh them when safe. If the Anthropic OAuth/token profile is stale, it suggests an Anthropic API key or the Anthropic setup-token path. Refresh prompts only appear when running interactively (TTY); `--non-interactive` skips refresh attempts.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/doctor.md:381:    - paired tokens whose scopes drift outside the approved pairing baseline\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/doctor.md:384:    Doctor does not auto-approve pair requests or auto-rotate device tokens. It prints the exact next steps instead:\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openresponses-http-api.md:76:- `max_output_tokens`: best-effort output limit (provider dependent).\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openresponses-http-api.md:295:downstream status/session surfaces, including `input_tokens` / `output_tokens`\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/openresponses-http-api.md:296:and `prompt_tokens` / `completion_tokens`.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/discovery.md:38:  - pairing tokens + ACLs owned by the gateway\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth.md:23:- You're hitting WebSocket `1008 unauthorized` errors because browsers can't pass tokens in WS payloads.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/pairing.md:30:4. On approval, the Gateway issues a **new token** (tokens are rotated on re‑pair).\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/background-process.md:68:- `send-keys`: send explicit key tokens or bytes to a PTY-backed session\n\n⚠️ [... middle content omitted — showing head and tail ...]\n\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/secrets.md:297:MCP server env vars configured via `plugins.entries.acpx.config.mcpServers` support SecretInput. This keeps API keys and tokens out of plaintext config:\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration.md:464:    - Hook auth is header-only (`Authorization: Bearer ***` or `x-openclaw-token`); query-string tokens are rejected.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/security/THREAT-MODEL-ATLAS.md:207:| **Description**         | Attacker steals authentication tokens from config files     |\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/auth-credential-semantics.md:57:- `oauth` profiles are not portable by default because refresh tokens can be\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:27:   Read-only diagnosis with log tail (tokens redacted).\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:196:    Token tip: long tasks and sub-agents both consume tokens. If cost is a concern, set a\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:614:    Do **not** commit anything under `~/.openclaw` (credentials, sessions, tokens, or encrypted secrets payloads).\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1148:    Copilot tokens are read from `COPILOT_GITHUB_TOKEN` (also `GH_TOKEN` / `GITHUB_TOKEN`).\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq-first-run.md:185:    and tokens stay at 0, the agent never ran.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq-first-run.md:657:    This stores OAuth tokens in auth profiles on the gateway host. Details: [Model providers](/concepts/model-providers).\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing.md:307:  - Runs the Telegram live QA lane against a real private group using the driver and SUT bot tokens from env.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing.md:633:The live-model Docker runners also bind-mount only the needed CLI auth homes (or all supported ones when the run is not narrowed), then copy them into the container home before the run so external-CLI OAuth can refresh tokens without mutating the host auth store:\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq-models.md:38:    parallelize long tasks (each sub-agent consumes tokens). See [Models](/concepts/models) and\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq-models.md:351:    - For OAuth profiles, sign in from the new agent when it needs its own account; otherwise OpenClaw can read through to the default/main agent without cloning refresh tokens.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq-models.md:387:    `request_too_large`, `input exceeds the maximum number of tokens`,\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq-models.md:388:    `input token count exceeds the maximum number of input tokens`,\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/context.md:25:- `/usage tokens` → append per-reply usage footer to normal replies.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/context.md:58:Session tokens (cached): 14,250 total / ctx=32,000\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/context.md:140:- **Inline shortcuts** (allowlisted senders only): certain `/...` tokens inside a normal message can run immediately (example: “hey /status”), and are stripped before the model sees the remaining text.\n/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/compaction.md:9:Every model has a context window: the maximum number of tokens it can process. When a conversation approaches that limit, OpenClaw **compacts** older messages into a summary so the chat can continue.[... 1950 more characters truncated]"}],"details":{"persistedDetailsTruncated":true,"originalDetailsBytesAtLeast":8193,"originalDetailKeys":["status","exitCode","durationMs","aggregated","cwd"],"status":"completed","cwd":"/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace","exitCode":0},"isError":false,"timestamp":1778118674648}}
{"type":"message","id":"dda75637","parentId":"1093afca","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:51:16.725Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_6IV4MH49oiQn38Riv27PH5R3|fc_0d371f2cfb221f1c0169fbf013ec0c8191961af2278f9050e1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-tools.md","offset":430,"limit":45}}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.5","usage":{"input":4825,"output":44,"cacheRead":30208,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":35077,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778118674772,"responseId":"resp_0d371f2cfb221f1c0169fbf01304e481918384c6543f094478"}}
{"type":"message","id":"d274d4a7","parentId":"dda75637","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:51:16.736Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_6IV4MH49oiQn38Riv27PH5R3|fc_0d371f2cfb221f1c0169fbf013ec0c8191961af2278f9050e1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"      - Matching model `contextTokens` preserves an explicit runtime cap when present; use it to limit effective context without changing native model metadata.\n      - Use `models.mode: \"replace\"` when you want config to fully rewrite `models.json`.\n      - Marker persistence is source-authoritative: markers are written from the active source config snapshot (pre-resolution), not from resolved runtime secret values.\n\n  </Accordion>\n</AccordionGroup>\n\n### Provider field details\n\n<AccordionGroup>\n  <Accordion title=\"Top-level catalog\">\n    - `models.mode`: provider catalog behavior (`merge` or `replace`).\n    - `models.providers`: custom provider map keyed by provider id.\n      - Safe edits: use `openclaw config set models.providers.<id> '<json>' --strict-json --merge` or `openclaw config set models.providers.<id>.models '<json-array>' --strict-json --merge` for additive updates. `config set` refuses destructive replacements unless you pass `--replace`.\n\n  </Accordion>\n  <Accordion title=\"Provider connection and auth\">\n    - `models.providers.*.api`: request adapter (`openai-completions`, `openai-responses`, `anthropic-messages`, `google-generative-ai`, etc). For self-hosted `/v1/chat/completions` backends such as MLX, vLLM, SGLang, and most OpenAI-compatible local servers, use `openai-completions`. A custom provider with `baseUrl` but no `api` defaults to `openai-completions`; set `openai-responses` only when the backend supports `/v1/responses`.\n    - `models.providers.*.apiKey`: provider credential (prefer SecretRef/env substitution).\n    - `models.providers.*.auth`: auth strategy (`api-key`, `token`, `oauth`, `aws-sdk`).\n    - `models.providers.*.contextWindow`: default native context window for models under this provider when the model entry does not set `contextWindow`.\n    - `models.providers.*.contextTokens`: default effective runtime context cap for models under this provider when the model entry does not set `contextTokens`.\n    - `models.providers.*.maxTokens`: default output-token cap for models under this provider when the model entry does not set `maxTokens`.\n    - `models.providers.*.timeoutSeconds`: optional per-provider model HTTP request timeout in seconds, including connect, headers, body, and total request abort handling.\n    - `models.providers.*.injectNumCtxForOpenAICompat`: for Ollama + `openai-completions`, inject `options.num_ctx` into requests (default: `true`).\n    - `models.providers.*.authHeader`: force credential transport in the `Authorization` header when required.\n    - `models.providers.*.baseUrl`: upstream API base URL.\n    - `models.providers.*.headers`: extra static headers for proxy/tenant routing.\n\n  </Accordion>\n  <Accordion title=\"Request transport overrides\">\n    `models.providers.*.request`: transport overrides for model-provider HTTP requests.\n\n    - `request.headers`: extra headers (merged with provider defaults). Values accept SecretRef.\n    - `request.auth`: auth strategy override. Modes: `\"provider-default\"` (use provider's built-in auth), `\"authorization-bearer\"` (with `token`), `\"header\"` (with `headerName`, `value`, optional `prefix`).\n    - `request.proxy`: HTTP proxy override. Modes: `\"env-proxy\"` (use `HTTP_PROXY`/`HTTPS_PROXY` env vars), `\"explicit-proxy\"` (with `url`). Both modes accept an optional `tls` sub-object.\n    - `request.tls`: TLS override for direct connections. Fields: `ca`, `cert`, `key`, `passphrase` (all accept SecretRef), `serverName`, `insecureSkipVerify`.\n    - `request.allowPrivateNetwork`: when `true`, allow HTTPS to `baseUrl` when DNS resolves to private, CGNAT, or similar ranges, via the provider HTTP fetch guard (operator opt-in for trusted self-hosted OpenAI-compatible endpoints). Loopback model-provider stream URLs such as `localhost`, `127.0.0.1`, and `[::1]` are allowed automatically unless this is explicitly set to `false`; LAN, tailnet, and private DNS hosts still require opt-in. WebSocket uses the same `request` for headers/TLS but not that fetch SSRF gate. Default `false`.\n\n  </Accordion>\n  <Accordion title=\"Model catalog entries\">\n    - `models.providers.*.models`: explicit provider model catalog entries.\n    - `models.providers.*.models.*.input`: model input modalities. Use `[\"text\"]` for text-only models and `[\"text\", \"image\"]` for native image/vision models. Image attachments are only injected into agent turns when the selected model is marked image-capable.\n    - `models.providers.*.models.*.contextWindow`: native model context window metadata. This overrides provider-level `contextWindow` for that model.\n    - `models.providers.*.models.*.contextTokens`: optional runtime context cap. This overrides provider-level `contextTokens`; use it when you want a smaller effective context budget than the model's native `contextWindow`; `openclaw models list` shows both values when they differ.\n\n[237 more lines in file. Use offset=475 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1778118676736}}
{"type":"message","id":"35e2d0ca","parentId":"d274d4a7","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:51:19.116Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_0c3uQnnzx328m8OOUEY0CWlK|fc_0d371f2cfb221f1c0169fbf016555c81918e03a15e94d569a1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/config-tools.md","offset":475,"limit":25}}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.5","usage":{"input":1391,"output":44,"cacheRead":34816,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":36251,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778118676861,"responseId":"resp_0d371f2cfb221f1c0169fbf0151ca08191ae71534a646f5d32"}}
{"type":"message","id":"758a38aa","parentId":"35e2d0ca","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:51:19.122Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_0c3uQnnzx328m8OOUEY0CWlK|fc_0d371f2cfb221f1c0169fbf016555c81918e03a15e94d569a1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"    - `models.providers.*.models.*.compat.supportsDeveloperRole`: optional compatibility hint. For `api: \"openai-completions\"` with a non-empty non-native `baseUrl` (host not `api.openai.com`), OpenClaw forces this to `false` at runtime. Empty/omitted `baseUrl` keeps default OpenAI behavior.\n    - `models.providers.*.models.*.compat.requiresStringContent`: optional compatibility hint for string-only OpenAI-compatible chat endpoints. When `true`, OpenClaw flattens pure text `messages[].content` arrays into plain strings before sending the request.\n\n  </Accordion>\n  <Accordion title=\"Amazon Bedrock discovery\">\n    - `plugins.entries.amazon-bedrock.config.discovery`: Bedrock auto-discovery settings root.\n    - `plugins.entries.amazon-bedrock.config.discovery.enabled`: turn implicit discovery on/off.\n    - `plugins.entries.amazon-bedrock.config.discovery.region`: AWS region for discovery.\n    - `plugins.entries.amazon-bedrock.config.discovery.providerFilter`: optional provider-id filter for targeted discovery.\n    - `plugins.entries.amazon-bedrock.config.discovery.refreshInterval`: polling interval for discovery refresh.\n    - `plugins.entries.amazon-bedrock.config.discovery.defaultContextWindow`: fallback context window for discovered models.\n    - `plugins.entries.amazon-bedrock.config.discovery.defaultMaxTokens`: fallback max output tokens for discovered models.\n\n  </Accordion>\n</AccordionGroup>\n\nInteractive custom-provider onboarding infers image input for common vision model IDs such as GPT-4o, Claude, Gemini, Qwen-VL, LLaVA, Pixtral, InternVL, Mllama, MiniCPM-V, and GLM-4V, and skips the extra question for known text-only families. Unknown model IDs still prompt for image support. Non-interactive onboarding uses the same inference; pass `--custom-image-input` to force image-capable metadata or `--custom-text-input` to force text-only metadata.\n\n### Provider examples\n\n<AccordionGroup>\n  <Accordion title=\"Cerebras (GLM 4.7 / GPT OSS)\">\n    The bundled `cerebras` provider plugin can configure this via `openclaw onboard --auth-choice cerebras-api-key`. Use explicit provider config only when overriding defaults.\n\n    ```json5\n\n[212 more lines in file. Use offset=500 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1778118679122}}
